Starting to check things off my list:   kayaking at Cava Beach &gt;  ;  dinner at Sesame Restauant &gt;

It was very hot here today, so luckily most of the walk to Cave Beach was shaded. I rode the bus to the promenade. While walking the path, I got to see the big sailing ship out at a distance.  When it went right by our apartment area the other day, I couldn't grab a camera fast enough. I had packed a light lunch and stopped to eat it at a park along the way--orange and apple slices, gouda cheese and some ice water.  I had frozen a bottle of water last night.  It worked nicely as an ice pack and then as my drink. (You think these carefree days are without some planning?)

Kayak Rental was only 40 kuna--not even $7, and I could have it for an hour. I asked the woman who rented them out if she'd take my photo and the keep my backpack behind the bar with her. That's another problem with going places alone.  I didn't want to leave it on a chair with camera, money, etc. And I wasn't going to bring it all in the kayak in case I flipped it over.

These sea kayaks are very steady compared to what I'm used to on Pleasant Lake. i first set off past Copacabana Beach and towards the beautiful suspension bridge.  Occasionally a larger boat was headed for the bridge, and gradually their wake would reach my kayak and rock it back and forth.  Fun! It was exciting to glance down as the paddle entered the water and see the aqua blue water, right down to the white rock bottom. So different than than the dark waters at our lake and you never see the bottom there.

I then paddled in the other direction, passing where I entered at Cava Beach and saw more swimming areas I didn't know about. One was a child-friendly,  gradually sloping beach and the other--let's just say the folks are never going to have to worry about uneven tan lines!

It was warm kayaking, although as I paddled,my legs were getting splashed.  A swim felt really good afterwards. While headed back, I found the Babin Kuk bus #6, so I figured I had enough exercise, considering the heat, and rode back.

Ed got home from work at 6 PM.  We raced through Old Town to try to catch the sunset at the beach bar, but it went behind some clouds.  Still pretty.  We then walked back through the town, heard some great music from the steps of St Blaise Church, then headed to Sesame Restaurant.  Its another favorite, right on Ed's route to work.  Delicious "Dalmation" roast beef dinner. Ended with a moon-lit walk back.  Great way to end the day.

