We got to meet our landlady today.  Her name is Luci and she came in from CA over the weekend. Her apartment here is right upstairs. She seems very nice and even picked us a bowl of grapes off the patio grape arbor. Also wants to have us up for coffee sometime.

Checking off a few more things from my list!  We walked the wall around Old Town this AM.  It was another hot one-close to 80 degrees before 10 and much hotter up on the wall. We brought  ice waters with us, but couldn’t resist the fruity drink at a little stop (Salvatores) along the way. We met a couple from Australia who took the picture of us.

It is so interesting to see the places with which we’ve become familiar from above them. Many have beautiful gardens out back or on their roofs. One even had a little grassy lawn and was out mowing! Must be the only lawn mower in all of Dubrovnik. From the sea of orange tile roofs you would not think there was any green at all, but people make the most of their “little piece of heaven” and have plants everywhere they can.

We were back at the apartment before noon.  Ed got ready to head to work for 1PM office hours and I got us caught up on laundry. Later in the afternoon I walked up to the beach behind his building, which had quite a few people for the quiet place it is.  I entered  the water from a new direction and discovered a cave! I was so excited (but held it in again).  I swam a little ways into it, at least until I was all under rock.  Very cool—just wish I had a picture of it.

We did get some great photos tonight of the sunset out on the Lapad peninsula. Our plan for the evening was to grocery shop, which we eventually did, but I couldn’t bear to spend sunset time in a store. So when Ed got home at 5, we headed to Lapad to the Hotel More beach café. We just ordered drinks because apparently you can’t get food outside at that time. It was such a perfect place to watch the sunset. Then we roamed inside their bar, which is a cave! So interesting. Around one table you can look down and see water. The ceiling is all lit up like little stars. Ed is definitely going back there with friends sometime. We ended up eating along the Promenade at Konavoka-always a great meal.

We grocery shopped at the Tommy and then took the bus home.  We each had a backpack full, plus carried two bags each. We figured Ed better load up on the heavy items while there are still two of us to carry things.

